<div id="review_257236754" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/257236754" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7351146-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366352435p2/7351146.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/257236754?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/7351146-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer257236754" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6387979600781606527">The feats included in this book are the substance of legend. Apologists in the contemporary era revel in perpetuating the Black Legend with regard to the Spanish conquistadors â which is largely resultant of centuries of British propaganda in an age of competing empires â but little attention is given to heinous accounts of cannibalism and human sacrifice in pre-conquest Mexico. Granted, this was all going on during the height of the Inquisition, and so many of the writings and traditions of pre</span>
  <span id="freeText6387979600781606527" style="display:none">The feats included in this book are the substance of legend. Apologists in the contemporary era revel in perpetuating the Black Legend with regard to the Spanish conquistadors â which is largely resultant of centuries of British propaganda in an age of competing empires â but little attention is given to heinous accounts of cannibalism and human sacrifice in pre-conquest Mexico. Granted, this was all going on during the height of the Inquisition, and so many of the writings and traditions of pre-Columbian civilization in the western hemisphere have been lost in the fires of Catholic dogmatism. Nevertheless, this particular primary source â indeed, this subject in general â remains an understudied and unbelievably remarkable chapter in colonial history.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6387979600781606527" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


