<div id="review_2823672309" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2823672309" />
    <a title="Kevin Cook" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39872471-kevin-cook"><img alt="Kevin Cook" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422931962p2/39872471.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2823672309?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin Cook" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin Cook" href="/user/show/39872471-kevin-cook">Kevin Cook</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780306813191" href="/book/show/174712.The_Discovery_And_Conquest_Of_Mexico">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2823672309" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10155706484232213272">First hand account and one of the most complete original sources on the topic of the Conquest of Mexico and the wars between the Spanish Conquistadors and the Aztecs. Raised on classroom overviews of the topic there is often the blackist of motives attributed to the Spanish as the aggressors in the conflict and the Aztecs being the conquered are mostly given a white washing of their motives. This account reveals the truth is much more interesting and that there was a rather a very logical chain </span>
  <span id="freeText10155706484232213272" style="display:none">First hand account and one of the most complete original sources on the topic of the Conquest of Mexico and the wars between the Spanish Conquistadors and the Aztecs. Raised on classroom overviews of the topic there is often the blackist of motives attributed to the Spanish as the aggressors in the conflict and the Aztecs being the conquered are mostly given a white washing of their motives. This account reveals the truth is much more interesting and that there was a rather a very logical chain of events that occurred that resulted in these two cultures coming into an inevitable clash. Bernal Diaz was not just a low ranking Soldier, he has the unique ability to evaluate the expedition as he was a captain who witnessed many of the important decisions that were made. While Bernal Diaz, certainly can be perceived as a biased writer, he does not come across as one. In fact, many of his relatives in Cuba were opposed to Cortez's expedition. In spite of this Diaz had a rather positive outlook on Cortez as a leader. Bernal Diaz, comes across as something of an old guard who is very thorough and trying to be honest in his narrative, covering logistics, causalities and day by day events in vivid detail. One can sense the emotions between Cortez and his Captains, his competitors, his allies and his enemies. He clearly wrote his account later in life as response to the many critical things people were claiming about their expeditions. By reading his account one sees first hand the evils of human sacrifice to idols, enslavement, cannibalism, and absolutism in Montezuma's empire. Rather than the usual anti-western Marxism of modern texts, this excellent account is pure and free of the fake revisionist history we see everywhere today. It puts you in the shoes of the conquistadors as he was facing sometimes overwhelming odds however it does not give an overly glorified picture of him either as Diaz does not hesitate to describe the early enslavements and acts of revenge that the conquistadors committed against the Indians as well. Anyone who wants to understand Mexico's early history should read this account. There are many lessons for leaders in this account as Cortez had to constantly fight open mutiny among his men<br /><br />Also as to all the comments you might see stating its dry or repetitive, I think detailed and day by day are more exact. My version was almost 500 pages and the author is a soldier from 500 years ago who is trying to describe everything that he remembers in detail so to give a complete account. When it comes to many first accounts this one is definitely one of the most detailed I have read, if that much detail bothers you stick to letting Wikipedia do your thinking for you. This is definitely a book for someone who is willing to take the time to comb through and find the many jewels of information inside it who wants to really understand the subject. People who just want to gain a basic understanding might find a Soldier's first hand account not the best book to start with.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10155706484232213272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

