<div id="review_181304515" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/181304515" />
    <a title="Redsteve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1858497-redsteve"><img alt="Redsteve" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509664800p2/1858497.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/181304515?book_show_action=true">Sep 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Redsteve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Redsteve" href="/user/show/1858497-redsteve">Redsteve</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781406754568" href="/book/show/2896062-bernal-diaz-del-castillo">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=period">period</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=spain-and-portugal">spain-and-portugal</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=renaissance">renaissance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=mexico-central-america">mexico-central-america</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=native-american">native-american</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1858497-redsteve?shelf=age-of-sail">age-of-sail</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer181304515" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16357931951754672619">Written in the mid-16th Century, this book feels quite different from many histories from this period; written from a &quot;soldier&apos;s eye&quot; view, the writing is straightforward with no attempt to present a polished or classical style. An impoverished hidalgo, Diaz travelled to the Americas to seek his fortune and became embroiled in Cortes&apos; conquest of what would later be called New Spain. His social standing was high enough for him to be involved in (and witness to) many top-level meetings (military </span>
  <span id="freeText16357931951754672619" style="display:none">Written in the mid-16th Century, this book feels quite different from many histories from this period; written from a "soldier's eye" view, the writing is straightforward with no attempt to present a polished or classical style. An impoverished hidalgo, Diaz travelled to the Americas to seek his fortune and became embroiled in Cortes' conquest of what would later be called New Spain. His social standing was high enough for him to be involved in (and witness to) many top-level meetings (military and diplomatic) during the Conquest. He also fought as a common soldier for much of the Conquest and gives a detailed perspective on the dangers and hardships they experienced. His descriptions of the land and people are vivid, if somewhat shallow in some cases. While a devout Christian and a loyal subject of the Emperor (Charles V), Diaz's main concern is money - he originally left the Spanish colonies because he was unable to get the lands he was promised on the islands - any gifts or loot he received was always valued to the peso. While obviously a big fan of Cortes, Diaz isn't shy about criticizing his leader either, especially when Cortes was stealing his soldiers' loot or losing his temper. Readable and fascinating.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16357931951754672619" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


