<div id="review_41040887" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/41040887" />
    <a title="Derek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1769635-derek"><img alt="Derek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1232848809p2/1769635.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/41040887?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek" href="/user/show/1769635-derek">Derek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer41040887" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2014238264217492185">DÃ­az is no journalist and no historian, and he wrote years after the fact apparently to refute the statements of other written accounts, and as a result this tale proceeds beginning to end as an extremely literal and weirdly detailed account, with more weight given to the number of horsemen sent on a particular attack than to his impressions of Aztec culture and the strange land the Spanish find themselves in. It is gracelessly written, with little eye for summation or high-level organization of</span>
  <span id="freeText2014238264217492185" style="display:none">DÃ­az is no journalist and no historian, and he wrote years after the fact apparently to refute the statements of other written accounts, and as a result this tale proceeds beginning to end as an extremely literal and weirdly detailed account, with more weight given to the number of horsemen sent on a particular attack than to his impressions of Aztec culture and the strange land the Spanish find themselves in. It is gracelessly written, with little eye for summation or high-level organization of the contents. The meandering sprawl of the narrative comes off as what it likely is: the verbal outpouring of an old man putting it all on paper before he passes.<br /><br />Despite this, it has moments that are weirdly fascinating. It is the story of a ragtag Spanish expedition set out from the Spanish-ruled West Indies colonies to explore and trade with the Central American mainland, who somehow wind up defeating a powerful Aztec city-state and becoming de facto overlords of Latin America, doing so despite internal strife as to Cortes's leadership and political rivalry in the Spanish court.<br /><br />In his own narrative, DÃ­az himself seems to disappear as a character. You get the impression that he is in some way present for the events, but without a clear idea of his role or personality. For the most part his actions and story merge with that of the body of soldiers, who he clearly most identifies with.<br /><br />What is clear from DÃ­az's point of view is that for the common soldiers, many of whom assumed great debt in even equipping and traveling to the American mainland, the expected wealth in plunder and opportunity in settlement did not materialize.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2014238264217492185" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


